"""
MKT Context Commentary — Nehemiah chapters 5–6
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-nehemiah-5-6.py

Ch 5: The debt-crisis narrative — Persian-period economic oppression and Nehemiah's fiscal reform
  - vv1-5: Triple-layered complaint (food insecurity → land mortgaging → taxation debt-slavery)
    exposing how Persian provincial taxation created systemic poverty in a subsistence economy
  - vv6-13: The assembly, the ryb (lawsuit/charge), the oath-ceremony administered by priests —
    Second Temple legal procedures for resolving covenant violations
  - vv14-18: The governor's table — Persian administrative provisioning norms and Nehemiah's deviation
  - v19: The Nehemiah Memoir's prayer-coda pattern (five such prayers total in the book)

Ch 6: Nehemiah's counter-intelligence and wall completion
  - vv1-4: The plain-of-Ono trap — geography, the meeting format, and Nehemiah's resistance
  - vv5-9: The unsealed-letter tactic — ANE epistolary norms and public shaming
  - vv10-14: Shemaiah the paid prophet — Second Temple false-prophecy sociology, sanctuary-asylum law
  - v15: The 52-day claim — its plausibility in light of archaeological and comparative evidence
  - vv17-19: Tobiah's network — inter-community marriage alliances and political espionage
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "5": {
    "1": "<p>The <strong>outcry</strong> (<em>ṣĕʿāqāh</em>) invokes a specific covenant-legal tradition recognized throughout Israel&rsquo;s collective memory. In the Pentateuch, the <em>ṣĕʿāqāh</em> triggers divine intervention: the cry of Egypt&rsquo;s slaves reaches YHWH (Exod 3:7), and the cry of Sodom signals a situation YHWH must investigate (Gen 18:20-21). The legal code in Exod 22:23-24 explicitly warns that oppressors will face YHWH&rsquo;s wrath when the oppressed cry out. By using this vocabulary, the narrator positions the economic crisis as a covenant issue — not merely a social or economic one — that obligates a covenant response. The inclusion of <strong>wives</strong> as co-complainants is unusual in OT legal contexts and suggests the emergency affected every level of household management.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The triple-layer complaint in vv2-4 reflects the specific mechanics of how Persian provincial taxation created a debt-spiral in a subsistence agricultural economy. The first group (v2) faces the most basic crisis: a large household with insufficient grain to eat. The Persian system collected taxes in silver, not in kind, which forced farmers to convert agricultural produce to silver through local markets — a disadvantage for small holders who had no price leverage. In years of poor harvest, the gap between food security and tax liability became acute. Nehemiah&rsquo;s community returned from Babylon in the early 5th century BCE to a land whose agricultural infrastructure had been disrupted by decades of disuse, Babylonian administration, and population reorganization. The &lsquo;famine&rsquo; mentioned in v3 likely refers to a short-term crop failure that exposed structural vulnerabilities in the community&rsquo;s economic base.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The pledge (<em>ʿāraḇnû</em>) of fields, vineyards, and houses to obtain grain during famine describes a well-attested mechanism in ancient Near Eastern economics: the pledge of land as collateral for a grain loan. Cuneiform documents from Babylonia and Persia reveal a sophisticated credit system in which land, orchards, and even persons could be pledged against debt. The problem was the structure of interest: typical ancient Near Eastern grain-loan rates were 20-33% annually, meaning a borrower who could not repay in the first harvest cycle owed more than the original principal. If the pledge was a mortgage-style agreement (the lender could occupy the land during the loan), the borrower lost productive capacity precisely when they needed it most to repay. The Deuteronomic code (Deut 15:1-11; 23:19-20) was designed to interrupt exactly this spiral, but enforcement in the Persian period appears to have been lax.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The <strong>king&rsquo;s tax</strong> (<em>middāt hammelek</em>) was the Persian imperial tribute — a fixed assessment per province paid in silver. Ezra 4:13 enumerates three types of Persian revenue collection: <em>middāh</em> (tribute), <em>bĕlô</em> (toll), and <em>hălāk</em> (customs). The <em>middāh</em> was the most fundamental, assessed on land. Persian tax records from the Persepolis Fortification Archive (Persepolis Fortification Tablets, discovered in 1933) document the provincial tribute system: local governors collected imperial taxes and forwarded them upward through the satrapal hierarchy. The tragedy of v4 is the compounding dynamic: the people had already pledged their fields to get grain (v3), and now they must borrow silver to pay the land tax on those same fields — which may now be occupied by creditors. They are paying rent on land they no longer effectively own.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The theological argument of v5 draws on the covenant concept of <em>ʿam ʾāḥad</em> (one people, one community). The phrase <em>kĕḇaśar ʾaḥêhem bĕśārênû</em> (&lsquo;as our brothers&rsquo; flesh is our flesh&rsquo;) echoes the kinship-solidarity ethic of the Mosaic covenant, under which all Israelites share common standing before YHWH. Leviticus 25:39-43 explicitly prohibits treating a fellow Israelite as a slave if he falls into poverty — he may become an indentured servant (<em>śāḵîr</em>, hired worker) but not a full chattel slave (<em>ʿeḇed</em>). The distinction matters: slave status was heritable and indefinite, while hired-servant status was contractually limited. The verb <strong>kōḇĕšîm</strong> (subduing, enslaving) suggests that full slave status, not merely hired labor, was being imposed on the children — a clear violation of Levitical law. The complaint that &lsquo;our hands are powerless&rsquo; (&lsquo;there is nothing in our hands&rsquo;) echoes the legal helplessness of those without property or standing in ancient courts.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Nehemiah&rsquo;s anger and the deliberate pause before action (v6-7) follows a pattern in Persian-period governance literature where a measured response to a grievance legitimizes the authority of the responding official. The Elephantine Papyri (Aramaic documents from the Jewish colony at Elephantine in Egypt, 5th century BCE) show that petitions to Persian officials typically required a formal deliberation period before action; impulsive action could itself be a sign of administrative unfitness. Nehemiah&rsquo;s <em>mĕlaḵtî ʾet-libbî</em> (my heart deliberated / I consulted with myself, v7) before acting is not hesitation but the appropriate procedural pause that marks a legitimate authority responding within established norms rather than in passion.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The <strong>formal charge</strong> (<em>wāʾrîḇāh</em>, from <em>ryb</em>) placed Nehemiah in the role of covenant plaintiff. The <em>ryb</em> (covenant lawsuit/dispute) is a well-documented literary and legal form in the OT: YHWH brings a <em>ryb</em> against Israel in Hos 4:1-3, Mic 6:2-8, and Jer 2:9. The <em>ryb</em>-form typically involves three elements: the statement of obligation (what was owed), the evidence of violation (what actually happened), and the demand for remedy (what must change). Nehemiah&rsquo;s charge against the nobles fits this structure. The audience — <strong>nobles and officials</strong> (<em>ḥōrîm wĕśĕgānîm</em>) — represents the two social tiers of the non-priestly ruling class in Persian Yehud: the <em>ḥōrîm</em> (freemen, aristocrats, landowners) and <em>śĕgānîm</em> (appointed officials, probably Persian administrative appointees). Both groups had economic leverage over the returning exiles who had less land tenure security.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Nehemiah&rsquo;s appeal to the practice of buying back exiles sold to foreign nations invokes a specific activity of the diaspora community. There is evidence from cuneiform business records (the Murashu Archive from Nippur, 5th century BCE) that wealthy Jewish families in Babylon did pay to redeem kin who had entered debt servitude to foreign creditors. The Murashu family were banking agents who managed large agricultural estates and debt contracts, and their records show Jewish names among both the debtors and the creditors. Nehemiah&rsquo;s point is that the community had spent resources on external redemption; now the nobles were re-enslaving the same people internally — making the external redemption work pointless. The rhetorical sting: <em>you are selling them back to us</em> (will we have to buy them back again?) frames the nobility&rsquo;s exploitation as undoing YHWH&rsquo;s redemptive work.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The appeal to <strong>fear of God</strong> (<em>yirʾat ʾĕlōhênû</em>) as the governing principle of economic justice reflects the Deuteronomic theology in which covenant obedience and social ethics are inseparable. The phrase <em>ḥerpat haggôyim</em> (the reproach of the nations) is a recurring concern in Ezra-Nehemiah (Neh 2:17; 4:2-4; 5:9): the community&rsquo;s conduct in the sight of their non-Jewish neighbors serves as a form of testimony to YHWH&rsquo;s character and the covenant people&rsquo;s distinctiveness. In an honor-shame culture, <em>ḥerpāh</em> (reproach/shame) was the most socially damaging accusation possible. For the surrounding nations to observe Israel oppressing its own members — while claiming to rebuild Jerusalem in the name of YHWH — would provide evidence that YHWH either did not care about justice or could not enforce covenant standards. The social ethics argument and the theological argument are one.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Nehemiah&rsquo;s concessive statement that he and his household had also been lending (<em>maššāʾ kesep wĕdāgān</em>, lending money and grain) is significant for understanding his position. He was not exempt from the economic pressures of the post-exilic community; he had also engaged in the credit economy. His proposal — <em>naʿăzĕḇāh nāʾ</em>, &lsquo;let us stop this&rsquo; — is thus a collective call to reform rather than an accusation from an uninvested outsider. The Deuteronomic law on interest (Deut 23:19-20) distinguished between lending to a &lsquo;brother&rsquo; (fellow Israelite, from whom no interest was permitted) and lending to a foreigner (from whom interest could be taken). In practice, the distinction may have collapsed in the Persian period under economic pressure, with the concept of &lsquo;brother&rsquo; being narrowed to exclude the poorest members of the community. Nehemiah restores its full Deuteronomic scope.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The demand to restore fields, vineyards, olive groves, and houses, along with the <strong>one-percent interest</strong> (<em>maʾat hakkesep</em>), raises a textual question that the original audience would have engaged with. The word <em>maʾat</em> most naturally means &lsquo;a hundredth&rsquo; (one percent), but the LXX renders it differently, and some scholars argue the word means simply &lsquo;a portion&rsquo; or &lsquo;a hundredth-part,&rsquo; which in context might mean the prevailing interest rate expressed as a fraction. Typical ancient Near Eastern agricultural loan rates in the Persian period were 20-40% annually; 1% per month (= 12% annually) was considered low. Whether Nehemiah is demanding that 1% be returned or that an entire interest schedule be cancelled, the core demand is the same: the assets taken in lieu of repayment must be restored, and the debt structure that enabled the taking must be unwound. The olive groves (<em>zêtîm</em>) are a significant addition — not just grain and grape production, but the olive oil economy (used for lamp fuel, food, and trade) was being controlled by creditor nobles.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The oath-ceremony administered by the priests following the assembly reflects Second Temple covenant-renewal practice. In the Mosaic covenant tradition, major commitments required divine witness and priestly mediation — a pattern seen in Josh 24 (the Shechem covenant renewal), Ezra 10 (the mass oath on the foreign-wife crisis), and Neh 10 (the community pledge). The <em>Elephantine Papyri</em> show that in the Persian-period Jewish community in Egypt, priests served similar roles in covenant oaths and community agreements. By calling priests (<em>hakkōhănîm</em>) to administer the oath, Nehemiah elevated the nobles&rsquo; promise from a social agreement to a sacred commitment — and simultaneously created a mechanism for accountability: breaking the oath was not merely a breach of contract but a religious offense with divine consequences.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The enacted curse with the garment-fold (<em>ḥōṣen</em>) is an example of the <em>symbolic action prophecy</em> tradition known across the ancient Near East. In ANE covenant-making, symbolic acts made curses vivid and binding. The most famous biblical example is the covenant of the pieces (Gen 15) in which parties walked between halved animals to invoke the curse &lsquo;may this happen to me if I violate this covenant.&rsquo; Jeremiah 34:18-19 references this practice explicitly. The robe-shaking gesture — shaking out the fold used for carrying objects, leaving it empty — enacted the curse of complete loss: may your house and assets become as empty as this shaken fold. The community&rsquo;s response <em>āmēn</em> (may it be so) formally ratified the enacted curse and their acceptance of its terms. The subsequent praise (<em>wayhallĕlû ʾeṯ-yhwh</em>) sealed the covenant ceremony as a worship act, not merely a legal one.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The precise dating of Nehemiah&rsquo;s governorship — &lsquo;the twentieth to the thirty-second year of Artaxerxes&rsquo; (445-433 BCE) — is characteristic of the Nehemiah Memoir&rsquo;s documentary style. Persian administrative records used regnal-year dating, a practice adopted in Jewish documents of the period (the Elephantine Papyri consistently date by regnal year). The <strong>governor&rsquo;s food allowance</strong> (<em>leḥem happeḥāh</em>) was a tax-in-kind that provincial governors were entitled to collect: grain, wine, oil, and animals from the local population above and beyond the imperial silver tax. Ezra 4:13 and Persian administrative documents confirm that governors had formal entitlements to local provisioning. Previous governors had apparently exercised these entitlements fully and added supplementary burdens beyond them (v15). Nehemiah&rsquo;s refusal to collect his food allowance was therefore a measurable economic relief — a real cost absorbed by him rather than the population.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The complaint that former governors took bread and wine plus <strong>forty shekels of silver</strong> per day (<em>ʾarbaʿîm šeqel kesep</em>) provides a rare quantified glimpse of Persian-period gubernatorial extraction. Forty silver shekels daily = roughly 456 grams of silver per day, or ~166 kg of silver per year. Comparative data from Mesopotamian administrative records (Neo-Babylonian temple archives) show that daily silver rations for senior officials were measured in fractions of a shekel; forty shekels per day would have been an enormous extraction for a small province like Yehud. Even their servants exercised authority over the population — the entire governor&rsquo;s household functioned as a patronage-extraction machine. The phrase <em>mirrāʾat ʾĕlōhîm</em> (because of the fear of God) is the sole stated reason for Nehemiah&rsquo;s restraint: not Persian law, not humanitarian instinct, but the covenant accountability to YHWH.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The specific detail that Nehemiah did not <strong>buy any land</strong> (<em>lōʾ qānîtî śādeh</em>) addresses the most common form of official corruption in ancient Near Eastern provincial governance: the acquisition of land by officials using their position to obtain distress sales or privileged access to defaulted properties. The Murashu Archive documents how wealthy families in Persia-controlled Babylonia accumulated large landholdings through exactly this mechanism — providing credit to small holders who then lost land to default. In Yehud, where the community&rsquo;s legitimacy rested on the Mosaic land theology (the land belongs to YHWH; each family has a covenant portion; cf. Num 36; Lev 25:23-28), land-acquisition by officials would have been especially egregious. Nehemiah&rsquo;s abstention from land acquisition is the flip side of his refusal to charge the food allowance — both represent the renunciation of standard official perquisites.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Nehemiah&rsquo;s table for <strong>150 Jewish officials</strong> plus visiting dignitaries reflects the Persian-period administrative practice of the governor&rsquo;s table as a site of political diplomacy and patronage. In the ancient Near East, sharing a meal at the ruler&rsquo;s table was a form of political incorporation: those who ate regularly at Nehemiah&rsquo;s table were, in effect, part of his political household. The <em>śĕgānîm</em> (officials) and their presence at the governor&rsquo;s daily table suggests a regular administrative court — a feature of Persian provincial governance as documented in Achaemenid sources. The inclusion of <em>visitors from the nations around us</em> (<em>min-haggôyim ʾăšer sĕḇîḇôtênû</em>) indicates that Nehemiah&rsquo;s table was also a site of inter-community diplomacy, receiving delegations from neighboring peoples — Ammonites, Moabites, Edomites, Samaritans — who had official relations with the province of Yehud.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The detailed daily provision list (one ox, six choice sheep, birds, and wine every ten days) in v18 mirrors ancient Near Eastern royal-household provisioning records known from Assyrian, Babylonian, and Achaemenid administrative texts. The Persepolis Fortification Tablets record daily ration distributions to workers, officials, and royal household members in precisely this format — quantities of grain, wine, beer, oil, and animals per day or per interval. The <em>bĕʿaśôr yāmîm</em> (every ten days) wine allotment specifies a formal ration cycle, not an ad hoc provision. By recording these details in his memoir, Nehemiah simultaneously demonstrates generosity (he fed the official court from his own resources), fiscal responsibility (the quantities are appropriate but not extravagant), and contrast with the previous governors (who extracted these same resources from the people rather than providing them).</p>",
    "19": "<p>The <strong>remember-me prayer</strong> (<em>zĕḵārāh-lî ʾĕlōhay</em>) at v19 is the first of five such petitions in the Nehemiah Memoir (5:19; 6:14; 13:14; 13:22; 13:31). This prayer form has been recognized as a literary signature of the memoir&rsquo;s genre: first-person administrative reports punctuated by brief petitionary prayers addressed directly to God. The form is paralleled in the Egyptian official&rsquo;s tomb inscriptions in which the official summarizes his deeds and asks for divine favor or a favorable afterlife judgment — but the Nehemiah Memoir redirects the appeal exclusively to YHWH rather than to a king or divine tribunal. The covenant theology behind the prayer is precise: YHWH&rsquo;s &lsquo;remembering&rsquo; (<em>zāḵar</em>) is his active, saving attention to covenant partners (Gen 8:1; 19:29; Exod 2:24); the request is not for a psychological act but for YHWH&rsquo;s covenantal response to Nehemiah&rsquo;s service.</p>"
  },
  "6": {
    "1": "<p>The <strong>plain of Ono</strong> (<em>biqʿat ʾônô</em>) was in the territory between Jerusalem and the coastal plain — approximately 35 km northwest of Jerusalem, near the border of Yehud&rsquo;s jurisdiction. The location was at the outer edge of or just beyond the province, which made the proposed meeting logistically suspicious: a journey of that distance for an informal meeting would have required Nehemiah to leave Jerusalem and the wall-building oversight for several days. In Persian-period Yehud, the provincial boundaries were closely associated with security and administrative integrity; leaving the provincial territory was not a neutral act. The fact that the opponents chose this specific location — accessible to them but at the margin of Nehemiah&rsquo;s operational territory — was itself a strategic choice designed to remove Nehemiah from his support network and the accountability of Jerusalem&rsquo;s population.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The proposed meeting &lsquo;in one of the villages in the plain of Ono&rsquo; appears to be an invitation for the kind of inter-provincial summit that Persian-period governors routinely held for trade, tax coordination, and dispute resolution. However, Nehemiah&rsquo;s observation that &lsquo;they were planning to do me harm&rsquo; reflects his awareness that such meetings could also be used for assassination, kidnapping, or the coercion of signatures on official documents. In the Persian period, diplomatic meetings between provincial officials were not always safe for the weaker party; records from Elephantine show that provincial administrators sometimes used formal meeting contexts to present pre-agreed outcomes and compel compliance. Nehemiah&rsquo;s four-fold refusal (vv2-4) may also reflect awareness that appearing at such a summit while the wall was unfinished would signal political weakness — the gates were still without doors (v1), meaning the city was not yet defensible.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Nehemiah&rsquo;s reply — <em>melaʾkāh gĕdôlāh ʾănî ʿōśeh</em> (&lsquo;I am doing a great work&rsquo;) — uses the vocabulary of sacred construction. The term <em>melaʾkāh</em> is the standard word for divinely commissioned construction work: the tabernacle (Exod 36:2-8; the workers are sent away because &lsquo;the melaʾkāh is sufficient&rsquo;), the temple (1 Chr 29:1; Ezra 3:8), and in earlier periods, divinely-given royal construction projects. By using this term, Nehemiah signals that the wall-building is not merely a civil-engineering project or a political initiative but a divinely commissioned task. In the Persian period, the legitimacy of a construction project often depended on demonstrated divine sanction — Cyrus&rsquo;s decree (Ezra 1) appeals to YHWH&rsquo;s authorization; Darius&rsquo;s affirmation of the temple project (Ezra 6) appeals to Cyrus&rsquo;s authorization. Nehemiah&rsquo;s rhetoric places his work in this authorized-by-YHWH category.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The four-fold repetition of the same message and the same reply (<em>ʾarbaʿ pĕʿāmîm kaddāḇār hazzeh</em>) follows a literary convention in Hebrew narrative prose for expressing persistent pressure and unshaken resolve. In the stories of Elijah and the Shunammite woman (2 Kgs 4:8-37), repeated insistence is the mark of faith; here, repeated refusal is the mark of discernment. Persian-period diplomatic correspondence was formal and iterative — a single refusal was not sufficient to close negotiations; multiple exchanges were the norm. Sanballat&rsquo;s four attempts may reflect a genuine diplomatic protocol (offer, counter-offer, adjustment) rather than mere stubbornness; Nehemiah&rsquo;s unvarying reply was itself a diplomatic message: this matter is not negotiable at any price.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The <strong>unsealed letter</strong> (<em>sefer pātûaḥ</em>) was a calculated humiliation. In ancient Near Eastern epistolary practice, letters were sealed — in Mesopotamia with clay tablets and cylinder seals, in the Persian period with wax or clay on papyrus or leather — to ensure confidentiality, authenticate the sender, and protect the message from tampering. An unsealed letter violated all three conventions: anyone who handled it along the route could read and discuss the contents, the lack of seal suggested the sender did not respect the recipient&rsquo;s dignity, and the opening of the letter to public view meant the accusations had already circulated before Nehemiah could respond. The strategy was to create the impression of guilt through publicity: by the time Nehemiah received the letter, its contents would already be rumored throughout the province. Sanballat&rsquo;s aide (<em>naʿărô</em>, his junior servant rather than a senior envoy) delivering the letter was a further insult to protocol — one sent a senior official to negotiate with a governor, not a servant.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The treason accusation in the letter — that Nehemiah was planning to rebel and make himself king — was precisely calibrated to Persian administrative law. The Achaemenid empire took <em>marduk</em> (rebellion) extremely seriously; the Behistun Inscription of Darius I (522-486 BCE) is essentially a long account of the rebellions Darius suppressed and the punishments he inflicted on rebel leaders. In Ezra 4:12-16, an earlier version of the same accusation had been used successfully to stop the rebuilding of Jerusalem under Artaxerxes&rsquo; predecessor: the letter to Artaxerxes claimed Jerusalem was historically a rebellious city, and Artaxerxes halted construction. Sanballat&rsquo;s letter was invoking a precedent that had already worked once. The additional claim that &lsquo;Geshem confirms this&rsquo; (<em>gešem ʾōmēr</em>) — naming the Arab regional power as a corroborating witness — added weight to the accusation, since Geshem (Gashmu) controlled significant territory in the western Arabian region (confirmed by a silver bowl inscription found at Tell el-Maskhuta) and was a credible witness to Persian administrators.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The accusation that Nehemiah had <strong>arranged for prophets to announce a king in Judah</strong> targeted a specific Persian fear: prophetically-legitimized royal pretenders. The Persian administrative memory included the crisis of pseudo-Smerdis (Cambyses II&rsquo;s false brother, who briefly claimed the throne in 522 BCE), and later Darius III would face similar pretender crises. The accusation that prophets were proclaiming a king in Judah would have resonated with Persian officials as a reference to the Davidic restoration hopes documented in Zechariah 9-14 and Haggai 2:20-23 (where Zerubbabel is addressed in quasi-royal terms). The accusation was not fabricated from nothing — messianic-Davidic hopes were genuinely present in the community; Sanballat was weaponizing those hopes by attributing them to Nehemiah personally.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Nehemiah&rsquo;s flat denial (<em>lōʾ-nihĕyu haddĕḇārîm hāʾēlleh</em>, &lsquo;none of these things happened&rsquo;) and counter-accusation that Sanballat was fabricating the story from his own imagination (<em>millib-bĕkā ʾattāh bādēʾm</em>) follows the standard form of official counter-correspondence in the Persian period. The Elephantine Papyri contain several examples of letters in which officials deny accusations and attribute fabrication to opponents. The verb <em>bādāh</em> (to invent/fabricate) is rare in the OT; its previous use at 1 Kgs 12:33 described Jeroboam&rsquo;s unauthorized innovations in religion, suggesting that the act of &lsquo;inventing from one&rsquo;s own heart&rsquo; is a specific type of illegitimate self-authorization in Israelite theological vocabulary.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The phrase <em>yirpenû yĕdêhem</em> (&lsquo;their hands would go limp/slack&rsquo;) is an idiom for demoralization and abandonment of a task found throughout the OT (Isa 13:7; Jer 6:24; 2 Sam 4:1; Job 4:3-4). In military contexts, &lsquo;slack hands&rsquo; meant a force that had lost the will to fight; in construction contexts, it meant workers who had stopped working under pressure. The prayer <em>ḥazzēq ʾeṯ-yādāy</em> (&lsquo;strengthen my hands&rsquo;) uses the precise antonym of <em>rāpāh</em> (slack/weak) — the Piel intensive of <em>ḥzq</em> (strong) — requesting the direct opposite of what the enemies intended. The second-person address to God in the middle of a historical narrative account (a flash-prayer inserted into the first-person memoir) is a characteristic feature of the Nehemiah Memoir&rsquo;s prayer-punctuation style, reflecting a Persian-period piety that saw divine agency operating in the midst of administrative affairs.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Shemaiah son of Delaiah son of Mehetabel was apparently a prophet known to Nehemiah — he went to his house, suggesting a pre-existing relationship. The detail that he was <em>ʿāṣûr</em> (confined, homebound) when Nehemiah visited has been interpreted variously: ritual confinement for prophetic preparation (cf. Jer 36:5 where Jeremiah is &lsquo;restricted/confined&rsquo; and sends Baruch in his place), claimed illness to create urgency, or staged dramatic self-confinement to heighten prophetic credibility. The proposal that they meet inside the temple (<em>ʾel-tôk hahêkāl</em>, inside the nave) appeals to a well-known ancient institution: temple sanctuary asylum. In the ancient Near East, temples provided asylum for those fleeing danger; 1 Kings 1-2 shows Solomon and Adonijah both using the altar of the Jerusalem temple as a sanctuary. Shemaiah&rsquo;s proposal exploited this institution to make the offer of a sanctuary meeting seem protective rather than sinister.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Nehemiah&rsquo;s refusal rests on two arguments, both rooted in specific Second Temple social and legal norms. The first is the honor-shame argument: a man in his position (<em>ûmî ʾăšer kāmônî</em>, &lsquo;who is like me&rsquo;) could not flee — flight in the face of threat would constitute an honor failure that would destroy his administrative credibility and signal weakness to both his community and his opponents. The second is the priestly-purity argument: the interior of the temple (<em>hêkāl</em>) was restricted to priests (Num 3:10; 18:7); a layman who entered would face divine judgment. The Second Temple period saw increasing attention to purity boundaries around the sanctuary: the Mishnah tractate Middot describes the concentric zones of diminishing access (Israelites, Levites, priests), and the violation of these zones was a capital matter. Nehemiah&rsquo;s awareness of this purity boundary was standard knowledge for an educated Judean of the period.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The discernment that <em>lōʾ ʾĕlōhîm šĕlāḥô</em> (God had not sent him) reflects the criteria for distinguishing true from false prophecy developed in Second Temple Judaism. The Deuteronomic false-prophecy test (Deut 18:20-22: if the prediction does not come true, the prophet is false) and the Jeremiah-era criterion (Jer 23:21-22: a true prophet has stood in the council of YHWH and heard his word; Jer 28:8-9: true prophets announced judgment, not peace) were well known in educated circles. By the 5th century BCE, a professional class of prophets-for-hire existed in Judah (cf. Mic 3:11: &lsquo;its prophets divine for money&rsquo;), and the Nehemiah community would have been familiar with the practice of paid prophecy. The financial transaction (<em>śĕḵārûhû</em>, they hired him) confirmed Nehemiah&rsquo;s discernment by providing an explanatory mechanism for the false prophecy: the motive was financial, not prophetic.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The strategy of using a paid prophet to induce Nehemiah to commit a specific, publicizable sin reflects a form of political entrapment known in ancient administrative contexts. If Nehemiah entered the sanctuary, two outcomes were possible: (1) he was struck down by divine judgment (confirming he was outside YHWH&rsquo;s protection), or (2) he was seen entering the restricted priestly area (confirming he had transgressed his authority and set himself above covenant law). Either outcome would damage his credibility with the community and with Persian authorities. The word <em>šēm rāʿ</em> (&lsquo;bad reputation/name&rsquo;) is the honor-vocabulary for the most effective non-violent attack on a leader: destroying their reputation before the community made them unable to govern. In an honor-shame society, reputation was not merely a social asset — it was the functional precondition for authority.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The mention of <strong>the prophetess Noadiah</strong> (<em>nôʿadyāh hanĕḇîʾāh</em>) and other unnamed prophets working against Nehemiah is a rare glimpse of the prophetic landscape of Persian-period Jerusalem. Female prophets were a recognized category in Israelite tradition (Miriam, Deborah, Huldah), and in the Second Temple period, the book of Isaiah&rsquo;s &lsquo;prophetess&rsquo; reference (Isa 8:3) and later Joel&rsquo;s prophecy that daughters would prophesy (Joel 2:28) suggest female prophetic activity was not eliminated but continued in modified forms. Noadiah&rsquo;s role as an opponent of Nehemiah — apparently part of a prophetic guild that had reasons to resist his centralizing authority — suggests she represented a prophetic tradition allied with the established Judean aristocracy (Tobiah&rsquo;s network) rather than with the returning diaspora group that Nehemiah represented. The imprecatory prayer against her (&lsquo;remember, O my God, what they did&rsquo;) treats her activity as equivalent to Tobiah&rsquo;s — a political-theological opposition to the reform agenda.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The claim that the wall was completed in <strong>52 days</strong> (from Av-Elul, approximately July-September 445 BCE) has been both questioned and defended by historians. Critical scholars have noted that Josephus (Antiquities 11.5.8) records the wall took two years and four months, apparently drawing on a different source or misreading of Nehemiah. However, archaeological evidence from Kathleen Kenyon&rsquo;s excavations in Jerusalem (1961-67) and Eilat Mazar&rsquo;s more recent work (2007-08) suggests that Nehemiah&rsquo;s wall may have been built largely by reusing and repairing earlier Iron Age walls rather than building from scratch — which would make a shorter construction timeline plausible. The organization of the workforce by family groups, each responsible for a section near their own home (Neh 3), is an efficient way to mobilize many small teams simultaneously rather than sequentially. Ancient parallels for rapid defensive-wall construction in emergency conditions exist in Mesopotamian and Egyptian records. The 52-day figure is not inherently implausible for a city wall that was largely a repair project with high motivation and distributed labor.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The <strong>collapse of enemy confidence</strong> (<em>wayyippĕlû mĕʾōd bĕʿênêhem</em>, &lsquo;they fell greatly in their own eyes&rsquo;) following the wall&rsquo;s completion reflects the ANE understanding that construction projects, especially defensive walls, were indicators of divine favor and political legitimacy. In the ancient Near East, a city with strong walls was under divine protection; a city with ruined walls was under divine abandonment. Sennacherib&rsquo;s campaign records boast of destroying city walls; the Lachish reliefs show the systematic dismantling of fortifications as the visible sign of conquest. The enemies&rsquo; recognition that the work was accomplished <em>mēʾēt ʾĕlōhênû</em> (from our God) is presented not as a conversion but as an involuntary acknowledgment — they could not find another explanation for the speed and success of the work. In Persian-period political theology, the success of a building project was routinely attributed to divine favor by all parties, including opponents.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The ongoing correspondence between the Judean nobility (<em>ḥōrê yĕhûdāh</em>, &lsquo;freemen/nobles of Judah&rsquo;) and Tobiah represents the complex social dynamics of the Persian-period Yehud community. Tobiah was an Ammonite official (<em>ʿeḇed</em>, servant/official, an honorific title rather than a servile one — cf. Neh 2:10 where he is &lsquo;Tobiah the Ammonite official&rsquo;). His network extended into the Judean aristocracy through marriage alliances (v18) and trade relationships. The Tobiad family is known from later sources — the Zenon Papyri (3rd century BCE) document the Tobiad family as a major economic and political force in Transjordan, suggesting that Tobiah&rsquo;s family parlayed their Persian-period connections into lasting regional influence. The letter-correspondence between the nobles and Tobiah was the intelligence network that made Nehemiah&rsquo;s opponents well-informed about internal developments in Jerusalem.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The double marriage connection between Tobiah and the Judean elite exposed the limits of the community boundary that Ezra&rsquo;s foreign-wife crisis (Ezra 9-10) had attempted to establish. Tobiah&rsquo;s father-in-law, Shecaniah son of Arah, was from a family that had returned from Babylon (Ezra 2:5: &lsquo;the sons of Arah&rsquo; = 775 persons), meaning Tobiah was not merely an outsider married into a peripheral family but was connected to one of the core returning-exile clans. His son&rsquo;s marriage to the daughter of Meshullam son of Berechiah (Neh 3:4,30: a wall-builder and prominent member of the community) suggests that the Tobiad network had penetrated even those families most actively involved in Nehemiah&rsquo;s building project. The sworn oaths (<em>baʿălê šĕḇûʿô</em>, those bound by oath to him) represent formal covenantal-commercial relationships — the community&rsquo;s social bonds cut across the political and ethnic boundaries that Nehemiah was trying to enforce.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The nobles&rsquo; practice of reporting Nehemiah&rsquo;s words back to Tobiah created a persistent intelligence problem that military security could not solve. In a community that depended on social trust for shared construction work, shared worship, and shared governance, the presence of a Tobiah-network inside the administrative community meant that any strategy or statement Nehemiah made in official contexts could be relayed to his opponents. Tobiah&rsquo;s ongoing letter-campaign designed to intimidate (<em>lĕyārĕʾāh</em>, to make him afraid) operated on the same principle as the unsealed letter (v5) and Shemaiah&rsquo;s prophecy (vv10-14): undermine Nehemiah&rsquo;s resolve through accumulated pressure rather than through any single decisive action. The five-pronged assault (the meeting invitation vv1-4, the treason letter vv5-9, the prophetic trap vv10-14, Noadiah&rsquo;s pressure v14, and Tobiah&rsquo;s letters v19) represents a sophisticated counter-strategy that, in retrospect, failed because Nehemiah addressed each threat separately and refused to be diverted from the work.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'nehemiah')
    merge_comm(existing, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'nehemiah', existing)
    total = sum(len(vv) for vv in CONTEXT.values())
    print(f'Nehemiah 5-6 mkt-context written ({total} verses: ch5={len(CONTEXT["5"])}, ch6={len(CONTEXT["6"])}).')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
